@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(x) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses an `if` as a VALUE in non-tail position (`let x = if …`).
-- The lowerer handles `if` only in TAIL position (the `If`/`Ret` decision-spine); as the
-- RHS of a `let` it reaches `normComp`'s default and is refused — a mid-expression `if`
-- needs a value-producing conditional (the same `Cond` short-circuit `&&`/`||` now use,
-- generalized to arbitrary branch values). The differential harness must report it
-- `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||` (lazy, lowered to a `Cond`; see
-- compile_shortcircuit_test). (Pipe `|>` was never a frontier — it desugars to a
-- saturated `Call`, e.g. `5 |> double` ≡ `double(5)`, and has compiled since D1(i).) The
-- frontier now sits at NON-TAIL `if` AS A VALUE. This file uses one, so it still refuses;
-- when value-position `if` lowers (a later D1 slice, reusing `Cond`), it flips from
-- `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let x = if 3 > 2 then 10 else 20
  println(x)
